"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674313","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The use of PAVA spray is an operational matter for the police, to be used in accordance with the NPCC Personal Safety Manual.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-19T15:28:42.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674313/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674313/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Police Custody: Riot Control Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on how many times pelargonic acid vanillylamide spray has been used in custody situations in each of the last five years; and what plans are in place to ensure that staff are trained to be aware of its proper use within the context of a custody suite.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674315","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>We are currently considering options for the publication of data related to Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children transferred to the UK under the Dublin Regulation and the criteria for section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, in line with the Immigration Minister and Minster for Vulnerable Children and Families’ Written Ministerial Statement (WMS) dated the 1 November 2016.</p><p>The WMS can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Lords/2016-11-01/HLWS231/" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Lords/2016-11-01/HLWS231/</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-24T11:31:52.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674315/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674315/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 16 January 2017 to Question 59797, if she will make it her policy to publish data on cases covered by the Dublin Regulation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","60384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674316","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>The UK has led the way within Europe in the processing of Passenger Name Records to counter terrorism-related activity, serious crime and other threats to the security of the UK border. The European Commission acknowledged that in its <em>“</em><em>First progress report towards an effective and genuine Security Union” </em>(COM(2016) 670), published on 12 October 2016 which noted in relation to the implementation of Directive 2016/681/EU: <em>“Member States now need urgently to build their Passenger Information Units (PIUs). So far, only one Member State (the United Kingdom) has set up a fully functioning PIU”.</em></p><p> </p><p>Domestic legislation has provided the necessary framework to establish and operate this capability. To the extent that any additional legislation, regulations or administrative provisions may be necessary for the purpose of transposing the Directive, the deadline for their completion is 25 May 2018.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-20T09:32:56.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674316/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674316/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Crime and Terrorism: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to bring forward legislative proposals for Directive 2016/681/EU on the use of passenger name record data for the prevention, detection, investigation and prosecution of terrorist offences and serious crime to be transposed into UK law.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","60387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674317","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>The UK already broadly fulfils the obligations set out in the Directive and these are reflected in our domestic laws.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-20T09:31:37.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674317/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674317/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Migrant Workers: Free Movement of People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to bring forward legislative proposals for Directive 2014/54/EU on measures facilitating the exercise of rights conferred on workers in the context of freedom of movement for workers to be transposed into UK law.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","60388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674318","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Government is taking the necessary measures to comply with this Directive by 22 May 2017.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2017-01-20T09:38:17.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674318/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674318/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","European Investigation Order","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to bring forward legislative proposals for Directive 2014/41/EU on the European Investigation Order in criminal matters to be transposed into UK law.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","60386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674319","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>We do not hold data on how many local authorities have specific anti-trafficking programmes. All local authorities in England and Wales have a duty under the Modern Slavery Act 2015 to notify the Home Office if they encounter a victim of modern slavery. They are also all ‘first responders’ under the National Referral Mechanism and so are able to refer victims for specialist support. Guidance on these referral processes is available on GOV.UK.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-01-24T11:28:59.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674319/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674319/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many local authorities have anti-trafficking programmes.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","60367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674320","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>The UK has a proud history of providing protection to those who need it, in accordance with our international obligations under the 1951 Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR). Over 8,000 children were granted asylum or another form of leave in the UK in the year ending September 2016.</p><p>Each claim for asylum is considered on its individual merits and asylum decision makers receive extensive training on considering asylum claims, including claims made from unaccompanied children. Protection is normally granted when a claimant establishes a well-founded fear of persecution under the Refugee Convention or their particular circumstances engage our obligations under Article 3 (ECHR).</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-20T14:59:05.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674320/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674320/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent steps she has taken to ensure that more unaccompanied children are granted asylum in the UK.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","60385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674321","Home Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>The National Crime Agency regularly publishes statistics relating to the number of potential victims of modern slavery referred to the National Referral Mechanism, broken down by police force area. These can be found here: www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/national-referral-mechanism-statistics. The Home Office has not made an assessment of the prevalence of human trafficking and modern slavery in Hertfordshire or the Hertsmere constituency.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-01-25T17:17:59.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674321/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674321/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Human Trafficking: Hertfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the prevalence of human trafficking in (a) Hertfordshire and (b) Hertsmere constituency.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","60380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674322","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Government received a request from the US Government to allow the transfer of Ravil Mingazov from the detention facility at Guantanamo Bay to the UK. After careful consideration, the Government declined this request. Mr Mingazov was transferred to the United Arab Emirates on 19 January 2017.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-25T16:59:14.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674322/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674322/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-17","Ravil Mingazov","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 17 January 2017 to Question 58526, whether the Government has received a request from the US administration to allow Ravil Mingazov, who is detained in Guantanamo, to be reunited with his family in the UK.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","60398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674323","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>As with right to work checks, the Right to Rent scheme is predicated on checks being carried out by third parties (in this case landlords and lettings agents). This means that the majority of illegal migrant prospective tenants will be denied access to the private rented sector as a result of these checks with no intervention by enforcement officers or reference to the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>Monitoring of the effects of the Right to Rent scheme on landlords and tenants is ongoing through the expert Landlords Consultative Panel, co-chaired by the Immigration Minister and Lord Best, an acknowledged expert in the fields of housing and planning. The Panel comprises bodies representing landlords, lettings agents, housing charities, local authorities and the Equality and Human Rights Commission amongst others. The Panel meets periodically, and communication channels outside these meetings allow for reporting by private rented sector and third sector groups of the experience of those they represent.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-24T11:34:37.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674323/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674323/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Undocumented Migrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on the number of undocumented migrants who have (a) left the UK voluntarily, (b) been made homeless and (c) occupied unsuitable or dangerous accommodation as a result of their being unable to access the private rented sector due to the provisions of the right to rent scheme.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","60411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674324","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>Fire and Rescue Authorities (FRAs) have delivered significant savings over the past five years. Fire-related fatality numbers and incidents can fluctuate between years, and despite a small increase in 2015/16, over the past 10 years there has been a 22 per cent decrease in the number of fire-related fatalities and a 52 per cent decrease in the total number of reported fires.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2009/10 single-purpose fire and rescue authorities’ non-ringfenced reserves rose by 153% to £602 million. These resources should be targeted at achieving long-term efficiencies.</p><p> </p><p>West Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Authorities’ non-ringfenced reserves rose from £7.3m in 2009/10 to £29m in 2015/16.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-23T17:06:06.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674324/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674324/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","West Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of funding changes on the effectiveness of the service provided by West Yorkshire Fire and Rescue Service since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","60404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674325","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Home Office and our asylum accommodation provider in Scotland are in regular contact with representatives from the Scottish Government and Glasgow City Council on accommodation standards through forums such as the Scottish Asylum Dispersal Strategy Group, Asylum Stakeholders Forum and the Scottish Asylum Procurement Group.</p><p>In Glasgow, all new property procurement proposals are individually considered by the Local Authority to ensure that they meet local legislation requirements.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-20T14:57:01.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674325/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674325/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Question 58482, what discussions the Government has had with (a) the Scottish Government and (b) Glasgow City Council on ensuring that contractors comply with the provisions of the Housing (Scotland) Act 2011 and relevant local authority rules.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","60419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674326","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>I am sorry but the Home Office does not hold the specific information in the format you have requested.</p><p>In order to determine the number of refusals for the reasons you have stated, the department would have to interrogate individual case records, at disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-20T14:55:17.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674326/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674326/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Entry Clearances: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many family visitor visas have been refused in each year since 2010 on account of reasonable doubt that the applicant for such a visa will leave the UK at the end of the visa period.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","60309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674327","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>In 2016, we transferred over 900 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children to the UK from Europe, including more than 750 from France as part of the UK’s support for the Calais camp clearance. Approximately 200 of these children met the criteria for section 67 of the Immigration Act.</p><p>More eligible children will be transferred from Europe, in line with the terms of the Immigration Act, in the coming months and we will continue to meet our obligations under the Dublin Regulation. In addition to our long standing secondee in Italy, we have seconded an expert to Greece who has been working closely with UNHCR, IOM and the Greek authorities to identify potentially eligible children under section 67 of the Immigration Act and support transfers under the Dublin Regulation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60307","2017-01-23T18:03:07.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674327/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674327/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress is being made on providing sanctuary for refugee children currently in France, Greece and Italy.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","60279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674328","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>This Government is clear that an attack on a police animal is a very serious offence. Whilst severe penalties are already in place to punish those who commit such crimes I am exploring with Ministerial colleagues and police leaders whether there is more that the law should do to offer the most appropriate protections to police and all other working animals. I have written to Ministerial colleagues at the Ministry of Justice and the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and will be meeting with them in due course to consider options further.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-19T15:46:28.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674328/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674328/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Police: Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with the (a) Ministry of Justice and (b) Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on penalties available for those convicted of causing injury to police support animals; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","60285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674329","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>A comprehensive list of Home Office public policy objectives and supporting targets is available on the GOV.UK website. For the period 2010 to 2015, the previous coalition government published ‘The Coalition: our programme for government’ which set out the key policy objectives for the government. The detailed Home Office objectives from this document were published in the Home Office Structural Reform Plan. The documents are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/78977/coalition_programme_for_government.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/78977/coalition_programme_for_government.pdf</a></p><p>and at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/structural-reform-plan--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/structural-reform-plan--2</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Following the General Election in May 2015, the Home Office, in common with other government departments has published a Single Departmental Plan which sets out current policy objectives. The current plan is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-single-departmental-plan-2015-to-2020" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/home-office-single-departmental-plan-2015-to-2020</a>.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-01-20T09:37:28.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674329/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674329/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Home Office: Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will provide a comprehensive list of the public policy targets established by her Department (a) between 2010 and May 2015 and (b) since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","60315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674330","Home Office","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Home Office website contains detailed guidance for customers on the process of applying for a visa.</p><p>Customer service is a key priority for UK Visas and Immigration, and the efficiency and effectiveness of the visa application process is kept under regular review, including by the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration. Feedback from customers and partners assists us in continuously improving the services we offer. For example, during 2016 we rolled out a new and more intuitive online visa application process, Access UK.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-04-25T12:45:26.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674330/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674330/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Visas: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that the family visitor visa application process is clear and comprehensible to people using that process.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","60318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674331","Home Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>The precise arrangements for controlling immigration after the UK leaves the EU have yet to be determined. However, as my Rt hon Friend, the Prime Minister, made clear in her Lancaster House speech on 17 January, the devolved administrations should be involved in the process of planning for the UK’s departure from the EU, and a Joint Ministerial Committee on EU negotiations has been established for this purpose.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-20T09:30:28.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674331/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674331/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Migrant Workers: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions her Department has had with each of the devolved institutions on immigration rules for seasonal agricultural workers after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","60266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674332","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Crime Survey of England and Wales estimated that there were 222,000 hate crimes on average each year from 2012/13 to 2014/15. This represents a decrease of 56,000 since the previous period covered by the survey. At the same time, the number of hate crimes recorded by the police rose from 44,471 in 2013/14 to 52,528 in 2014/15. This increase in recorded crime is welcome as it is likely to reflect improved police practice and victim confidence in coming forward to report crimes.</p><p> </p><p>The difference between the crime survey figures and the police recorded figures shows that hate crimes continue to be significantly under-reported. The Hate Crime Action Plan published on 26 July 2016 includes action to increase the reporting of hate crime, including making greater use of third party reporting centres.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-01-24T11:29:53.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674332/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674332/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment her Department has made of the extent of the under-reporting of hate crimes.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674333","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>It is a matter for the police to record the outcomes of their operations to tackle knife crime, including arrests and weapons seizures. The Home Office does not hold this information.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","60303","2017-01-23T17:03:41.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674333/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674333/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Knives: Seized Articles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of knife seizures resulted in an arrest in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674334","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>It is a matter for the police to record the outcomes of their operations to tackle knife crime, including arrests and weapons seizures. The Home Office does not hold this information.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","60302","2017-01-23T17:03:41.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674334/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674334/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Knives: Seized Articles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of weapon sweeps aimed at tackling knife crime resulted in a weapon seizure in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674335","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The decision to procure and deploy body worn video (BWV) cameras is an operational one for Police and Crime Commissioners and chief officers. Most forces in England and Wales use BWV to some extent. Each force will have its own implementation plan and schedule for the rollout of cameras.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-19T13:48:55.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674335/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674335/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many body-worn cameras are held as resources by police forces in (a) total and (b) each police force area in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674336","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Government has, and continues to, work closely with partners within the UK and across Europe to ensure the timely and effective transfer of children to the UK under the Dublin Regulation and section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. The date on which an unaccompanied child refugee arrives in a local authority will depend on both when the child is brought to the UK, which will be agreed with the country in which they currently reside, and on the availability of a placement in the local authority that has agreed to participate in the National Transfer Scheme.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60292","2017-01-24T13:32:16.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674336/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674336/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the average time taken to accommodate unaccompanied child refugees in the areas of local authorities that have offered to do so.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","60294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674337","Home Office","false","2017-01-23","<p>In 2016, we transferred over 900 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children to the UK from Europe, including more than 750 from France as part of the UK’s support for the Calais camp clearance. Approximately 200 of these children met the criteria for section 67 of the Immigration Act.</p><p>More eligible children will be transferred from Europe, in line with the terms of the Immigration Act, in the coming months and we will continue to meet our obligations under the Dublin Regulation. In addition to our long standing secondee in Italy, we have seconded an expert to Greece who has been working closely with UNHCR, IOM and the Greek authorities to identify potentially eligible children under section 67 of the Immigration Act and support transfers under the Dublin Regulation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60279","2017-01-23T18:03:07.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674337/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674337/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made on the implementation of the Dubs amendment to bring unaccompanied child refuges in Europe into the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","60307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674338","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Government has, and continues to, work closely with partners within the UK and across Europe to ensure the timely and effective transfer of children to the UK under the Dublin Regulation and section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. The date on which an unaccompanied child refugee arrives in a local authority will depend on both when the child is brought to the UK, which will be agreed with the country in which they currently reside, and on the availability of a placement in the local authority that has agreed to participate in the National Transfer Scheme.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","60294","2017-01-24T13:32:16.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674338/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674338/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, at what date unaccompanied child refugees will arrive in Cambridge.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","60292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674339","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>We will continue to meet our obligations under the Dublin Regulation and more unaccompanied children will be transferred to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act in the coming months. An announcement will be made in due course on the total number of children to be transferred to the UK under the Immigration Act.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-24T11:33:30.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674339/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674339/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of how many unaccompanied child refugees will be brought to the UK in 2017.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","60293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674340","Home Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. How much of the policing budget is allocated to a specific workstream or activity within a police force area is a matter for individual Police and Crime Commissioners in consultation with their Chief Constable. The Government is absolutely clear that harassment and abuse in whatever form and whoever the target is totally unacceptable. This includes harassment committed in person, or using phones or the internet.</p><p>There is a robust legal framework to tackle offline and online harassment and abuse provided by the Protection from Harassment Act 1997, and offences in the Malicious Communications Act 1998 and the Communications Act 2003.</p><p>New Authorised Police Professional Practice on stalking and harassment is currently being developed by the College of Policing, and Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate will shortly be commencing a joint inspection of how stalking and harassment are handled by police forces and the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), including the service received by victims.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","60218 ; 60359 ; 60360","2017-01-25T17:23:38.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674340/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674340/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Harassment: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of the policing budget in England and Wales was spent on investigation of online harassment in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674341","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. How much of the policing budget is allocated to a specific workstream or activity within a police force area is a matter for individual Police and Crime Commissioners in consultation with their Chief Constable.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","60355 ; 60358 ; 60361","2017-01-19T15:44:08.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674341/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674341/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Fraud: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of the policing budget in England and Wales was spent on investigation of online fraud in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674342","Home Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. How much of the policing budget is allocated to a specific workstream or activity within a police force area is a matter for individual Police and Crime Commissioners in consultation with their Chief Constable. The Government is absolutely clear that harassment and abuse in whatever form and whoever the target is totally unacceptable. This includes harassment committed in person, or using phones or the internet.</p><p>There is a robust legal framework to tackle offline and online harassment and abuse provided by the Protection from Harassment Act 1997, and offences in the Malicious Communications Act 1998 and the Communications Act 2003.</p><p>New Authorised Police Professional Practice on stalking and harassment is currently being developed by the College of Policing, and Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary and Her Majesty’s Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate will shortly be commencing a joint inspection of how stalking and harassment are handled by police forces and the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), including the service received by victims.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","60216 ; 60359 ; 60360","2017-01-25T17:23:38.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674342/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674342/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Harassment: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of the policing budget in England and Wales was spent on prevention of online harassment in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","60218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674343","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Government continues to engage closely with UK based charities from the humanitarian, peace-building and development sectors on a range of issues relating to compliance with Counter Terrorism legislation. Comprehensive guidance for the sector on the range of legislative frameworks covering the activities of NGOs overseas was provided by the Government in November 2015 and is reviewed as required.</p><p>In addition, the Government recently appointed an independent expert adviser to work alongside officials, regulators, the banking sector and charities to progress new thinking on ways that this community can implement robust compliance and due diligence processes that are in accord with Counter Terrorism legislation. This engagement is ongoing.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2017-01-24T16:20:31.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674343/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674343/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress has been made by the Government-NGO Working Group in findings ways to mitigate the direct and indirect effect of counter-terrorism legislation on humanitarian, peace-building and development non-governmental organisations.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","60241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674344","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>Applications for a visa to travel to the UK to visit family are considered on their merits, in accordance with the requirements set out in Appendix V to the Immigration Rules, taking into account the information and supporting documents provided in the application.</p><p> </p><p>It is for the applicant to satisfy the decision maker that they meet those requirements, including that they are a genuine visitor. A genuine visitor is a person who will leave the UK at the end of the visit, will not live in the UK for extended periods or make the UK their main home, has sufficient funds for their support during the visit and who intends to undertake permitted visit activities and not prohibited activities. The assessment of the genuineness of a visitor relates to the particular factors of the individual application, but may include the applicant’s personal and economic ties to their country of residence.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-24T13:57:54.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674344/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674344/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-17","Visas: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what criteria are used to determine whether an applicant is likely to leave the UK by the end-date of a family visitor visa.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","60226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674345","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>DFID DRC provides civil society organisations with practical and technical support to educate some 5.8 million citizens on their civic rights and responsibilities, to eliminate illegal school fees, to empower young women and, indirectly, in health, water and sanitation.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-24T16:28:44.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674345/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674345/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Democratic Republic of Congo: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing to civil society in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","60221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674346","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>DFID’s funding to the African Union (AU) includes support for election monitoring, strengthening governance and building the AU’s capacity for early warning in countries at risk of instability, such as the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).</p><p>Through the cross-government Conflict, Security and Stabilisation Fund, the UK supports wider AU work on prevention, management and resolution of conflict including AU mediation efforts in DRC via its Liaison Office in Kinshasa. This is fundamental to promoting poverty reduction as well as strengthening the UK’s national security.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-24T16:30:40.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674346/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674346/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Democratic Republic of Congo: African Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing to the African Union to assist it in its work in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","60222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674347","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>The UK currently provides support to increase the democratic representation of women and youth, protect human rights defenders and broaden electoral observation activities.</p><p>Last year, we announced that additional funding would be made available to update the national electoral roll, if all parties were prepared to hold free, fair and timely elections. That offer remains on the table, and the recent political accord signed in the DRC is a marker of growing commitment to hold elections.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-24T16:47:03.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674347/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674347/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Democratic Republic of Congo: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support she plans to offer to the Democratic Republic of the Congo to help it hold the presidential elections in that country planned for 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","60223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674348","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>The <a href="http://dlca.logcluster.org/display/public/DLCA/2.1+Yemen+Port+Assessment" target="_blank">UN logistics cluster</a> has publically available information on Yemen’s wider port capacity.</p><p>The largest cranes in the port of Hodeidah, Yemen’s largest port, have been severely damaged by the conflict in Yemen which is restricting humanitarian and commercial access. The World Food Programme is procuring mobile cranes for Hodeidah port to improve capacity and we expect these to arrive imminently. Furthermore, ships chartered by humanitarian actors tend to have on-board cranes meaning some cargo can be unloaded onto the port.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-24T17:13:34.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674348/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674348/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Yemen: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment of the adequacy of the provision of cranes in Yemen's ports for the delivery of humanitarian aid.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","60203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674349","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Supreme Court Judgment in June 2016 ruled that the 2008 House of Lords decision (which confirms that the BIOT Constitution Order 2004 is lawful) stands and as such there are no plans to restore the right of abode in the British Indian Ocean Territory.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-25T16:08:59.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674349/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674349/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-17","Ilois: Resettlement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Supreme Court judgment in Bancoult in June 2016, if he will restore the right of abode to the Chagossian people.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","60248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674350","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>DFID‘s work in Iraq is focused on supporting the Government of Iraq-led, UN-supported humanitarian and stabilisation response to the current crisis, and DFID funding is channelled through UN agencies and non-governmental organisations. DFID is not directly funding programmes supporting joint working between the UK and Iraqi public sectors.</p><p>The British Council is working with the Iraqi health, heritage and education sectors to foster collaboration with UK institutions. Through the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) the UK is also working with the Government of Iraq to train and mentor the Iraqi Government Digital Service to support online communications in the campaign against Daesh.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-24T17:12:02.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674350/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674350/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Iraq: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to encourage collaboration between the UK and Iraqi public sectors (a) in health, (b) in education and (c) more widely.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","60249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674351","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-20","<p>The recent ICAI report on DFID’s cash transfer programmes found good achievement on alleviating poverty and vulnerability for the poorest households. DFID is currently considering how best to respond to the recommendations in the ICAI report, and will publish a response on 9<sup>th</sup> February.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-01-20T15:19:13.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674351/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674351/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Developing Countries: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that maximum value for money is delivered by cash transfer schemes overseas.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","60262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674352","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>DFID funds clearance of cluster munitions, landmines and other explosive remnants of war irrespective of their origin through its Global Mine Action Programme, through the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund, and through the DFID Afghanistan programme. The Global Mine Action Programme has delivered 2,086ha of land back to productive use, saving lives and supporting livelihoods.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-24T17:09:46.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674352/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674352/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her Department's policy to provide direct funding to ensure the clearing of UK-produced cluster munitions.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","60296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674353","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-24","<p>DFID is contributing £112 million to the crisis in Yemen this financial year, none of which is used to help with the clearing of cluster munitions. The majority of this funding is used to provide life-saving humanitarian assistance, such as food, clean water, medical supplies and emergency shelter.</p><p>Through the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund, the UK is contributing £700,000 for 2016/17 to support the UN Development Programme (UNDP) to clear mines and explosives in Yemen, including cluster munitions.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-24T17:06:31.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674353/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674353/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-17","Yemen: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of direct aid for Yemen committed in the current financial year has been used to help with the clearing of UK-produced cluster munitions.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","60295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674354","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-27","<p>Information about the Ministry of Justice’s policy commitments is in the public domain in a number of formats. Like all government departments we publish our Annual Report and Accounts in June or July each year. This is scrutinised through the select committee process. Annual Reports are available on gov.uk</p><p> </p><p>Single Departmental Plans set out the strategic objectives, priorities and headline indicators for each department. These are currently being refreshed and will be updated by the end of April 2017.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-01-27T14:07:39.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674354/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674354/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-17","Ministry of Justice: Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will provide a comprehensive list of the public policy targets established by her Department (a) between 2010 and May 2015 and (b) since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","60317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674355","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>This specific information is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-23T17:27:46.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674355/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674355/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-17","Stun Guns: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many convictions there have been for the possession, purchase or acquisition without authority of (a) stun guns and (b) tasers under the Firearms Act 1968 in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","60284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674356","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-27","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-27T13:59:46.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674356/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674356/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-17","Prisons: Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information she holds on the number of ambulance call-outs to prisons in England and Wales in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","60240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674358","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-16","<p>The Government is committed to improving diversity of opportunity and creating an inclusive working environment that attracts the best talent and makes the most of potential skills and productivity of ex-offenders in the community.</p><p>The Civil Service has committed to banning the box, following the former Prime Minister's commitment in February 2016. Business in the Community's Ban the Box campaign was formally launched across the Civil Service on the 17th October 2016.</p><p>A number of departments are already operating their recruitment process in line with the Ban the Box principles. This approach is now being formalised across the Civil Service and departments are working to implement this initiative quickly and effectively to ensure their roles attract the widest possible range of applicants. The Cabinet Office is responsible for the Ban the Box policy in the Civil Service.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice is supportive of the initiative and will explore options for promoting Ban the Box across both the Public and Private sector to increase opportunities available to offenders.</p><p>Information about the number of business signed up to the initiative is not held by the MoJ. The Business in the Community campaign maintain the list and it can be accessed here: <a href="http://www.bitc.org.uk/programmes/ban-box/who-has-banned-box-0" target="_blank">http://www.bitc.org.uk/programmes/ban-box/who-has-banned-box-0</a></p><p>The information requested relating to how many MoJ employees have unspent convictions could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-16T11:15:53.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674358/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674358/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-17","Criminal Records: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress the Government has made on its ban the box initiative; which businesses have signed up to that initiative; how many employees of her Department have unspent convictions; what progress has been made on that initiative across the wider public sector; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","60212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674359","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-20","<p>I welcome yesterday’s announcement that a public inquiry into the Renewable Heat Incentive will now go ahead. I believe that this is important to build confidence in the ability of the institutions to deliver and help set the tone for the election to come. This is a devolved issue and it is right and preferable that an inquiry has been agreed at Stormont.</p><p> </p><p>I would encourage full co-operation with the inquiry, and hope that it is able quickly and effectively to establish the facts, and provide assurances to the public. For our part, the Government will do everything we can to support this independent inquiry.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-01-20T12:59:47.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674359/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674359/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-17","Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what his policy is on the circumstances in which he would establish an independent inquiry into the renewable heat incentive scheme in Northern Ireland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","60421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674360","Prime Minister","false","2017-01-20","<p>As my Office confirmed in September, the Business Advisory Group was disbanded as part of a process to review and broaden business engagement structures.</p><p>I have maintained a high level of business engagement across all sectors and parts of the UK.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-01-20T10:54:46.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674360/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674360/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-17","Business Advisory Group: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when the Prime Minister's Business Advisory Panel last met; and when it next plans to meet.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","60371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674361","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-20","<p>I refer the hon Member to my answer of 20 December to Question 57840 (http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=57840).</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-20T13:11:27.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674361/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674361/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","Railways: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 7 December 2016 to Question 55987, on what dates (a) his and (b) predecessor departments received force majeure claims from train operating companies in relation to industrial action since January 1996; and what the outcome was in each such case.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","60336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674362","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-20","<p>As requested, Chris Gibb has provided advice to the Secretary of State, much of which is already being taken forward. Chris Gibb is now working on developing his advice into a set of recommendations which will be published in due course.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-20T13:16:10.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674362/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674362/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to publish the (a) key findings and (b) full report of Chris Gibb's project board into rapid improvements of Southern Rail.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","60337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674363","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Department for Transport’s Single Departmental Plan sets out its four objectives. Tackling air quality supports all of these objectives, but it is particularly important for delivering safe, secure and sustainable transport.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s plans for tackling air quality are set in the National Air Quality Plan for Nitrogen Dioxide, published December 2015, which will be updated shortly.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-20T13:20:11.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674363/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674363/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's objectives are related to air quality.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","60213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674364","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-24","<p>There are no current plans to replace Pendolinos. It will be for the operator of the West Coast Partnership franchise, which will begin in April 2019, to decide their future fleet strategy on the classic network.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-24T13:34:22.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674364/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674364/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","West Coast Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has for the replacement of Pendolino trains with trains of at least equal speed on the West Coast Mainline when Pendolino trains come to the end of their serviceable life.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","60205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674365","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Government remains committed to delivering the Great Western Modernisation Programme delivering passenger benefits including the new IEP trains that will be entering service on this route later this year.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-20T13:24:02.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674365/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674365/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","South Wales Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will carry-out a feasibility study for electrifying the rail line from Cardiff to Swansea.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","60243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674366","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Government will consult shortly on airspace matters. This consultation will include a draft of new guidance to the Civil Aviation Authority on the environmental factors it should take into account when exercising its air navigation functions.</p><p> </p><p>It is expected that the revised guidance will be in place by the end of this year.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-24T13:26:55.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674366/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674366/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","Aviation: Impact Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph B.18 of the Civil Aviation Authority's Guidance on the application of the airspace change process document, published in March 2016, whether guidance will be issued to airports on their needing to conduct an impact assessment on livestock, animals and biodiversity.","false","Biography information for Michelle Thomson","Edinburgh West","Michelle  Thomson","60256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674367","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-24","<p>The government has committed to spend over £600m this parliament to encourage the uptake of ultra low emission vehicles in the UK. Precise annual budgets for the next five years have not been set, but we expect over £100m to be spent during this Parliament, ensuring the UK remains at the forefront of ultra low emission vehicle technology development. To date, every £1 of Office for Low Emission Vehicles funding through Innovate UK’s Low Carbon Vehicle Innovation Platform has been forecast to return £20 to £34 over 15 years.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-01-24T13:30:59.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674367/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674367/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 59476, what estimate he has made of the total amount to be spent by his Department on the development of ultra-low emission technology for road vehicles in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","60289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674368","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Airports Commission in its Final Report and supporting documents published in July 2015, considered potential options for improving capacity on the M4 motorway between junctions 2 and 4 in relation the expansion of Heathrow airport.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Government’s consideration of the Airports Commission’s work and recommendations, Highways England assessed and validated the costs and deliverability of the Commission’s strategic road proposals, which were published in October 2016 alongside Government’s announcement of its preference for a new northwest runway at Heathrow airport.</p><p> </p><p>The Department recognises that future improvements to the M4 may be needed for a number of reasons to address future transport demand, including wider population and economic growth, but not solely as a result of the proposed expansion of Heathrow airport.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will be considering the need for potential future improvements for the strategic road network, including the M4, as part of its long term investment planning processes for development of future Road Investment programmes.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will set out details about plans for a new runway at Heathrow airport in Parliament through a draft National Policy Statement shortly. It will be subject to a full and public consultation and parliamentary scrutiny.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","60278","2017-01-20T12:53:50.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674368/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674368/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","Heathrow Airport: M4","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to consult on the Airports Commission's Surface Access Works: Strategic Road Network Proposals for the expansion of Heathrow Airport which relate to the M4 between junctions 2 and 4.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","60277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674369","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Airports Commission in its Final Report and supporting documents published in July 2015, considered potential options for improving capacity on the M4 motorway between junctions 2 and 4 in relation the expansion of Heathrow airport.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Government’s consideration of the Airports Commission’s work and recommendations, Highways England assessed and validated the costs and deliverability of the Commission’s strategic road proposals, which were published in October 2016 alongside Government’s announcement of its preference for a new northwest runway at Heathrow airport.</p><p> </p><p>The Department recognises that future improvements to the M4 may be needed for a number of reasons to address future transport demand, including wider population and economic growth, but not solely as a result of the proposed expansion of Heathrow airport.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will be considering the need for potential future improvements for the strategic road network, including the M4, as part of its long term investment planning processes for development of future Road Investment programmes.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will set out details about plans for a new runway at Heathrow airport in Parliament through a draft National Policy Statement shortly. It will be subject to a full and public consultation and parliamentary scrutiny.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","60277","2017-01-20T12:53:50.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674369/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674369/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-17","Heathrow Airport: M4","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Airports Commission's Surface Access Works: Strategic Road Network (SRN) Proposals, whether his Department will publish further details of the SRN surface access proposals for the expansion of Heathrow Airport which relate to the M4 between junctions 2 and 4.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","60278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674370","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>The information requested is not available. However, in the month of December 2016 there were 970 people claiming Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit. This does not include people claiming Employment and Support Allowance and Incapacity Benefits as the extent to which these claimants are required to attend the Jobcentre will vary, depending upon the specific requirements of the benefit they receive.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-20T15:11:44.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674370/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674370/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people use the Anniesland Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","60330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674371","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-23","<p>The information requested is not available. However, there were 54 new claims made to Employment and Support Allowance at Anniesland Jobcentre in December 2016.</p><p> </p><p>It is worth noting that the extent to which people claiming Employment and Support Allowance and Incapacity Benefits are required to attend the Jobcentre will vary depending upon the specific requirements of the benefit they receive.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-23T14:15:33.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674371/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674371/answer","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674371/answer/previousversion/31245","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with disabilities use the Anniesland Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","60331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674372","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>It is important to remember that the announcements in Glasgow are just proposals at this stage and not final decisions. Posters are prominently displayed at Anniesland Jobcentre and customers are being made aware when attending the office.</p><p> </p><p>Jobcentre staff will offer advice to customers on the options available in terms of alternative offices, should it be necessary to do so and after a decision has been made.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-20T15:11:28.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674372/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674372/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people using the Anniesland Jobcentre have been informed in writing of the potential closure of that jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","60329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674373","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Child Maintenance Service (CMS) does not take into account a person’s “lifestyle” in calculating a maintenance liability.</p><p> </p><p>The CMS has access to income information held by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC), allowing us to capture a much wider range of income types received by Paying Parents. The definition of income within the 2012 scheme includes almost all additional sources of gross income captured by self-assessment. We refer to this as “unearned income” and it includes incomes from property, savings and investments (including dividends) and other miscellaneous incomes.</p><p> </p><p>This provides a more effective route to taking these kinds of income into account than the “lifestyle” ground which existed for the previous schemes of maintenance.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-20T10:36:32.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674373/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674373/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Child Maintenance Service takes account of a person's lifestyle as well as income in determining liabilities for paying maintenance.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","60320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674374","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>The total budget for Contracted Employment Programmes for 2016-17 is £426.6m. It is not possible to publish the disaggregation of this figure to individual programmes, as this is subject to change throughout the year.</p><p> </p><p>We are unable to provide any information for future years as funding has not yet been finalised at this level of detail.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-20T15:10:55.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674374/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674374/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Employment Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department plans to spend on (a) the Work Programme and (b) Work Choice in each year until those programmes cease to operate.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","60321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674375","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>Final referrals to the Work Programme will be made as per contracts on 31 March 2017. Participants will receive up to 104 weeks on the programme and the date for the final participant to complete the programme is 29 March 2019. The final qualifying claim for a sustained job outcome is 26 June 2021.</p><p> </p><p>Current Work Choice contracts are due to end during April 2017. The precise dates vary according to individual contract.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-20T15:09:28.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674375/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674375/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Employment Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what date he has set for the cessation of (a) the Work Programme and (b) Work Choice.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","60322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674376","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-23","<p>UK State Pensions are payable worldwide under domestic legislation. There are no plans to change this policy.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-23T15:12:05.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674376/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674376/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is his policy to retain the principle of exportability for state pensions when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","60254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674377","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-23","<p><strong></strong></p><p>The information as requested is not available. However, there are a total of 5,790 people claiming Employment and Support Allowance and Incapacity Benefits in Glasgow South constituency. It is worth noting that the extent to which they are required to attend the Jobcentre will vary, depending upon the specific requirements of the benefit they receive.</p><p> </p><p>The purpose of the equality analysis and public consultation is to help establish how many people are likely to be affected by these proposals, including disabled people of working age in Glasgow South constituency.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-23T14:11:50.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674377/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674377/answer","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674377/answer/previousversion/31263","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has plans to estimate the number of disabled working age population in Glasgow South constituency to inform the equality impact assessment on the proposed closure of Glasgow jobcentres.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","60228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674378","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>Enforcement charges are intended to encourage parents to comply with their commitments, as well as to help off-set the administrative cost of taking enforcement action. The enforcement charges are lower than the actual cost to the Department for taking the action. To charge the full cost could have an adverse effect and encourage non-compliance, as well as being potentially disproportionate to the size of the debt. The levels are designed to be proportionate to the type, and seriousness, of the order that is being pursued.</p><p> </p><p>Enforcement charges are only collected once the ongoing maintenance and any arrears due have, been paid.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-20T10:42:56.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674378/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674378/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria were used to determine the Child Maintenance Service's enforcement charges, including liability orders, lump sum reduction orders, regular deduction orders and deduction from earnings orders and requests.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","60231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674379","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>It’s our duty to make sure that this group is supported not just financially but also to fulfil their potential. That is why we have put in place a new employment support package of £330m over 4 years which was developed together with stakeholders to help disabled people to move closer to the labour market.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-20T10:54:17.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674379/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674379/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what evidential basis he took into account in making recent changes to financial support for disabled people new to the employment and support allowance work-related activity group.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","60215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674380","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Department currently has no plans to collect and publish this information for individual Jobcentre Plus offices.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does publish Employment and Support Allowance statistics to various geographical levels, including constituency (Westminster and Scottish), local authority and Jobcentre Plus district. These can be found here: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found here: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a>.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-20T13:59:22.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674380/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674380/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Employment and Support Allowance: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57955, on employment and support allowance: Glasgow, if he will take steps to make available the information requested.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","60227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674381","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-20","<p>The Government wants to build an economy that works for everyone, where low wage workers are fairly rewarded for their contribution to the UK economy.</p><p>We believe that it is essential for employers to ensure that their reward packages are competitive, in order to retain and develop the workers who are fundamental to their success. However, it is ultimately for employers to decide how they manage increases in their wage bill. The Government will hence continue to set a minimum hourly wage, and remuneration above that rate is a contractual matter for the employer and worker.</p><p>The Government has committed to ensuring a competitive business environment. The Government’s increase in the Employment Allowance, and reduction in employers’ National Insurance contributions, is estimated to benefit up to 500,000 businesses and charities, and the government’s cuts to the main rate of corporation tax will benefit over a million companies, allowing them to increase the pay of their workers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-20T13:53:22.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674381/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674381/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-17","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to encourage employers to consider paying above the minimum wage levels set in legislation.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","60394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674382","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-23","<p>Throughout a participant’s time with their Work Programme provider, Jobcentre Plus will continue to see them to check they are meeting their conditions for claiming benefits, if applicable. It is the provider’s responsibility to ensure that nothing they require of participants prevents them from attending these appointments.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-23T15:16:42.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674382/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674382/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether participants in the Work Programme are required to attend meetings at jobcentres during their work placement.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","60382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674383","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Department does not provide any financial subsidy to employers or organisations who offer work experience to participants on the Work Programme.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-24T13:11:35.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674383/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674383/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department provides employers who participate in the Work Programme with a financial subsidy for their participation.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","60383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674384","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-23","<p>Work experience undertaken through the Work Programme is unpaid. Participants will therefore remain on Jobseeker’s Allowance whilst participating on a work placement.</p><p>As the placements are unpaid, employers are not required to pay National Insurance contributions for participants.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","60437","2017-01-23T16:03:54.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674384/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674384/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the participants in the Work Programme receive a wage from employers in addition to their jobseeker's allowance payments during their placement.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","60435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674385","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-23","<p>It is the responsibility of Work Programme providers to pay a participant’s travel costs as travel expenses are included within the funding received from DWP as part of the overall contract package. Before starting a work placement the provider should discuss with the participant the practical arrangements for getting to and from the employer, including reimbursement of travel expenses.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-23T15:58:43.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674385/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674385/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-17","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether (a) employers and (b) his Department pays travel expenses for participants in the Work Programme.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","60436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674386","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-20","<p>The safe decommissioning of the Pile Fuel Storage Pond is a priority of the hazard and risk reduction programme at Sellafield. The entire bulk stocks of historic nuclear fuel have now been removed from this nearly 70 year old facility, and the assessed radioactive hazard risk associated with the facility has been reduced by 70%.</p><p> </p><p>The current life time plan budget for emptying the Pile Fuel Storage Pond of fuel and waste, and decommissioning the facility in line with the agreed end state for the Sellafield site is approximately £1bn.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-20T14:54:47.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674386/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674386/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-17","Sellafield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the cost of (a) emptying the Pile Fuel Storage Pond at Sellafield, (b) full radiological and toxicological decontamination of that pond and (c) conditioning, packaging and final long-term management of the spent nuclear fuel recovered from that pond.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","60332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674387","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-20","<p>All Freedom of Information requests are considered on a case-by-case basis taking into account all the circumstances of the case at the time the request is made. If the Department considered that information within the scope of a request would, or would be likely to, prejudice the commercial interests of any person (including the public authority holding it) and the balance of the public interest favoured withholding it, subject to applicable law, then the information would not be disclosed.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-20T13:49:27.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674387/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674387/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-17","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what criteria his Department plans to use when considering requests by a generating party to the investor agreement on Hinkley Point C nuclear power plant that information on that agreement requested under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 should be considered commercially sensitive.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","60333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674388","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-20","<p>In November and December 2016 the Green Investment Bank (GIB) incorporated twelve new Special Purpose Vehicles (SPVs): Galloper Holdco Limited; OSW Co Holdings 1 Limited; OSW Co Holdings 2 Limited; OSW LP Holdco Limited; Project G Holdco Limited; Project G Holdings 1 Limited; Project G Holdings 2 Limited; Rampion Holdco Limited; WMR Holdco Limited; Rampion Investco Limited; New Green Interim Holdco Limited; and UK Green Investment Lyle Limited.</p><p>The SPV ‘UK Green Investment Lyle Limited’ was incorporated in the course of business-as-usual to support GIB’s investment in the Lincs offshore wind farm (publicly announced by GIB on 13 January 2017).</p><p>The remaining eleven SPVs were incorporated in order to facilitate the potential introduction of private capital in to a number of GIB’s offshore wind assets, following discussion between GIB and the UK Government. These entities are currently dormant and own no assets.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","60232 ; 60233 ; 60234 ; 60235","2017-01-20T14:48:26.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674388/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674388/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-17","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 59325, on whose instruction the 10 new subsidiary companies were established at the Green Investment Bank in November and December 2016.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","60236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674389","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-20","<p>The issues considered by the Review are wide-ranging and complex, as they relate to an untried technology in the marine environment. The Government is currently assessing the recommendations set out in the Review, and will consider the issues which would arise from a broader lagoon programme. A Government response will be published in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-20T14:52:27.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674389/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/674389/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-17","Tidal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to respond to the Hendry Review.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","60229"
