"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673447","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-19","<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Office" target="_blank">The Office</a> for Budget Responsibility’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook (November 2016) includes the latest forecasts for oil and gas. The November Outlook indicates a downward trend in planned capital expenditure in the oil and gas sector, from £10.1 billion in 2016 to £3.7 billion in 2021. This reflects a lower oil price and its consequential effect on overall production.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has taken unprecedented action to support jobs, investment and activity in the UK and UK Continental Shelf. Budget 2016 announced a £1 billion package of fiscal reform, supporting the industry through the challenging commercial conditions caused by the steep fall in oil prices. Lower tax rates will improve the economics of new investment and future discoveries. The basin-wide Investment Allowance, introduced in 2015, further reduces the effective rate of tax for many companies, including at the exploration stage.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of these changes, the UK now has one of the most competitive tax regimes for oil and gas in the world, supporting jobs and investment.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","60017 ; 60018 ; 60020","2017-01-19T15:26:23.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673447/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673447/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-16","Fossil Fuels: Exploration","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to boost oil and gas exploration in the UK continental shelf.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","60019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673448","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-19","<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Office" target="_blank">The Office</a> for Budget Responsibility’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook (November 2016) includes the latest forecasts for oil and gas. The November Outlook indicates a downward trend in planned capital expenditure in the oil and gas sector, from £10.1 billion in 2016 to £3.7 billion in 2021. This reflects a lower oil price and its consequential effect on overall production.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has taken unprecedented action to support jobs, investment and activity in the UK and UK Continental Shelf. Budget 2016 announced a £1 billion package of fiscal reform, supporting the industry through the challenging commercial conditions caused by the steep fall in oil prices. Lower tax rates will improve the economics of new investment and future discoveries. The basin-wide Investment Allowance, introduced in 2015, further reduces the effective rate of tax for many companies, including at the exploration stage.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of these changes, the UK now has one of the most competitive tax regimes for oil and gas in the world, supporting jobs and investment.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","60017 ; 60018 ; 60019","2017-01-19T15:26:24.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673448/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673448/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-16","Fossil Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of fiscal changes made in the Budget 2016 on levels of employment in the UK oil and gas sector.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","60020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673449","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is responsible for ensuring charities and donors claim only the reliefs to which they are entitled. The legislation on Gift Aid is at sections 413 to 430 Income Tax Act 2007. Guidance for donors can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/donating-to-charity/gift-aid" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/donating-to-charity/gift-aid</a>. Guidance for charities can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/claim-gift-aid/overview" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/claim-gift-aid/overview</a>.</p><p> </p><p>It is the role of the Charity regulators to ensure charities are publicly accountable for the management of their funds (including Gift Aid) and have used them for their stated charitable purposes. The Charity Commission is responsible for the regulation of all charities in England and Wales. Charities in Scotland and Northern Ireland are regulated by the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator and the Charity Commission for Northern Ireland respectively.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-24T10:19:53.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673449/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673449/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-16","Gift Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what (a) guidance and (b) regulations apply to the allocation of Gift Aid funds by charities in receipt of such funds.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","60155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673450","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>Policy proposals to help vulnerable people and low income households to access and maintain tenancies in the Private Rented Sector were discussed at recent meetings of the Affordability &amp; Security Working group. The group is made up of representatives from across the housing sector to look at what more we can do to improve affordability and security within the private rented sector. The working group’s final report is due to be submitted to ministers for consideration by the end of January.</p><p>We are committed to preventing homelessness. That is why we have protected £315 million for local authority homelessness prevention funding, secured £149 million central government funding in this Parliament, and we are supporting Bob Blackman’s Homelessness Reduction Bill, which will ensure that everyone who needs it, is supported to prevent a homelessness crisis.</p><p>We recently announced the allocation of our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme which is supporting 84 projects covering 225 areas all over England to provide an innovative approach to tackling homelessness, with prevention at its heart. This includes £20m for those at imminent risk of sleeping rough to secure accommodation and get them back on their feet.</p><p>We are also investing £100 million to deliver low-cost accommodation for those ready to move on from a homelessness crisis – including rough sleepers leaving hostel accommodation. Details of the bidding process outside London will be announced by the Homes and Communities Agency in the spring.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-02T14:43:19.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673450/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673450/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673450/answer/previousversion/31252","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Private Rented Housing: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 12 January 2017 to Question 58921, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of re-introducing funding for private rented sector access schemes to support single homeless people to access private rented housing.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","60156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673451","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not collect ths information.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-24T13:41:11.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673451/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673451/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673451/answer/previousversion/31254","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Universal Credit: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people who are registered with local authorities in England as being homeless receive universal credit payments.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","60168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673452","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-20","<p>We do not want to impose a set of design or development principles on communities. We want to support local authorities and communities in developing their own vision for locally-led garden towns and villages, taking account of local plans. We expect to see ambitious proposals that set high standards for design, quality and the provision of green space.</p><p>We are working with local areas to establish how best to measure and ensure those ambitions are being delivered.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-20T14:39:45.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673452/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673452/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how his Department plans to measure whether proposed new garden cities, towns and villages are attractive and well-designed; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673453","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-20","<p>We are currently supporting the development of ten new locally led garden communities of more than 10,000 homes at Ebbsfleet, Bicester, Didcot, Basingstoke, Otterpool Park in Kent, Aylesbury, Taunton, Harlow &amp; Gilston, North Essex and North Northamptonshire.</p><p>We do not have a pre-set view of how many more garden communities of more than 10,000 homes we may support. We are encouraging local areas to be ambitious and want to see proposals that will provide high quality, transformational housing growth.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-20T14:38:13.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673453/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673453/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many garden towns of more than 10,000 homes his Department plans to fund in the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673454","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-20","<p>We are determined that new garden cities, towns and villages are supported by the right infrastructure at the right time. We have committed £15 million of capacity funding to support master planning and key studies to underpin joined up delivery of new housing and infrastructure in the garden cities, towns and villages. Our new £2.3 billion Housing Infrastructure Fund shows just how serious we are about ensuring that infrastructure is in place to support housing growth.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","60162","2017-01-20T14:19:49.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673454/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673454/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on how schools, hospitals, libraries and other public services will be planned into the proposed new garden cities, towns and villages.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673455","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-20","<p>We are determined that garden cities, towns and villages are underpinned by the right infrastructure at the right time. Garden Cities should be locally led and I stand ready to consider innovative proposals put forward by local areas.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-20T14:52:47.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673455/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673455/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of allowing private firms to construct and run physical infrastructure usually provided by public bodies in the proposed new garden cities, towns and villages.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673456","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-20","<p>The principles set out in the National Planning Policy Framework(NPPF) on the location of development in general apply equally to garden cities, towns and villages. The announcement of government support for a garden city, town or village does not in any way pre-judge the planning process. We would expect local authorities to work within the context of the NPPF and of policies set out in their Local Plan, and also ensure that the usual opportunities for interested individuals and groups to engage with these proposals and make representations are provided.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-20T14:42:51.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673456/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673456/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to allow proposed new garden cities, towns and villages to go ahead on the sites of (a) airfields, (b) playing fields and (c) other community spaces.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673457","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-20","<p>We are determined that new garden cities, towns and villages are supported by the right infrastructure at the right time. We have committed £15 million of capacity funding to support master planning and key studies to underpin joined up delivery of new housing and infrastructure in the garden cities, towns and villages. Our new £2.3 billion Housing Infrastructure Fund shows just how serious we are about ensuring that infrastructure is in place to support housing growth.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","60159","2017-01-20T14:19:49.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673457/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673457/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on how publicly owned physical infrastructure will be planned into the proposed new garden cities, towns and villages.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673458","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework is clear that planning permission should be refused for development resulting in the loss or deterioration of irreplaceable habitats, including ancient woodland, unless the need for, and benefits of, the development in that location clearly outweigh the loss.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-19T17:51:52.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673458/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673458/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Forests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of protection for ancient woodland in the National Planning Policy Framework.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","60178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673459","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-20","<p>These figures are published by Ebbsfleet Development Corporation, which was set up by Government to deliver the Ebbsfleet Garden City. This, and other performance data, is available here:</p><p><a href="http://ebbsfleetdc.org.uk/tracking-our-performance/" target="_blank">http://ebbsfleetdc.org.uk/tracking-our-performance/</a></p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-20T14:17:08.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673459/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673459/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673459/answer/previousversion/31048","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Ebbsfleet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many homes have been built in Ebbsfleet Garden City.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","60021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673460","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Government has no plans to exempt NHS premises from business rates. Hospitals, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-19T16:33:11.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673460/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673460/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","NHS: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential benefits of exempting NHS premises from business rates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","60032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673461","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>DCLG does not hold data on the cost of collection by type of property.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-19T16:32:42.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673461/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673461/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","NHS: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the cost of billing for and collection of business rates from NHS premises in (a) Southampton and (b) England was for 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","60033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673462","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>As at 31 December 2016, 74 per cent of land in England is covered by an adopted Local Plan.</p><p>We want all areas to be covered by an up to date plan and that is why we have bought forward a statutory requirement in the Neighbourhood Planning Bill for local planning authorities to identify strategic priorities, and set out policies to address them in their development plan documents.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-19T16:35:27.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673462/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673462/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Local Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of land in England is covered by an adopted local plan.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","60038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673463","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>There is no requirement for the Department to be notified when a neighbourhood plan is adopted. Our records show that 268 neighbourhood plans have been adopted in England since April 2013.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-19T16:33:36.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673463/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673463/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Neighbourhood Development Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many neighbourhood plans have been adopted in England.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","60039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673464","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-02","<p>I refer to the Department's response to the written question HL4037 answered on 28 December 2016, which sets out the potential revenue raised for all local authorities:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2016-12-12/HL4037/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2016-12-12/HL4037/</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-02T14:44:20.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673464/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673464/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673464/answer/previousversion/31251","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of revenue to be raised by the social care precept in (a) Southampton, (b) the five poorest local authorities and (c) the five wealthiest local authorities in England in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","59989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673465","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-30","<p>a) Information on how much each local authority received in revenue support grant is collected and published online through the Revenue Expenditure and Financing Outturn statistics.</p><p>Data, as reported by local authorities, for revenue support grant received are available in the Revenue Summary (RS) tables within the local authority data outturn collections:<br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing</a></p><p>These are available from 2007-08 to 2015-16. Provisional data for 2016-17 is scheduled for publication in August 2017</p><p><strong>Please note: </strong>The revenue support grant forms part of the Department for Communities and Local Government’s annual Local Government Finance Settlement. The calculation of how local government is funded differs year on year. Therefore figures may not be wholly comparable across the time-series.</p><p>Additionally, between 2008-09 and 2009-10 there was local authority restructure so any data prior to 2009-10 is not comparable to later information.</p><p>b) The amount of business rates collected by each authority is available in the National Non-Domestic Rates publication online.</p><p>The local authority data for business rates collected are available as part of the ‘NNDR3’ data collection here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/national-non-domestic-rates-local-authority-level-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/national-non-domestic-rates-local-authority-level-data</a></p><p>This is published and available from 2008-09 to 2015-16. Data for 2016-17 is provisionally scheduled for publication in November 2017</p><p><strong>Please note: </strong>There have been changes to the business rates and council tax policy since 2013-14. From April 2013, business rates moved from being a centrally redistributed function to one where the local government sector retains a percentage of what they collect. This change aims to increase the proportion of local authority spend that is financed by locally retained income, over which authorities will have more control. As part of the 2015 Spending Review, this is set to increase to 100% rate retention by 2020.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-30T16:31:13.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673465/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673465/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673465/answer/previousversion/31037","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much each local authority (a) received in revenue support grant and (b) collected in business rates in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","60080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673466","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>Our <em>Locally-led Garden Villages, Towns and Cities </em>prospectus makes clear that the garden villages proposals we support should be free-standing settlements of between 1,500 and 10,000 homes. These though are locally-led proposals and it is for local areas to decide the appropriate number of homes in garden cities, towns or villages over time. Our support for garden cities, towns and villages in no way pre-judges the planning process and, subject to any planning freedoms that may be agreed with individual places, the usual planning rules apply.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-19T16:28:56.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673466/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673466/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether it is his policy for proposed garden cities, towns and villages to expand indefinitely or be limited to a size at which more stringent planning rules will apply.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673467","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Secretary of State has received one representation on the proposed New Bermondsey Development. As Lewisham Council are currently considering making a compulsory purchase order to secure land for a proposed regeneration scheme, and any compulsory purchase order has to be submitted to the Secretary of State for confirmation, I cannot comment further at this stage so as not to prejudice his consideration.</p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-19T16:34:17.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673467/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673467/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Millwall Football Club: Lewisham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations he has received on planning policies and legislation that could affect Millwall FC's continued location in Lewisham; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","60082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673468","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-26","<p>The planning and development control system considers whether a proposal would unacceptably affect amenities and the existing use of land and buildings which ought to be protected in the public interest. Where such matters are material considerations, they must be taken into account and weighed against the merits of the proposed development.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-26T16:12:13.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673468/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673468/answer","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673468/answer/previousversion/31250","Biography information for Lord Barwell","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Garden Communities: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to compensate residents living in the vicinity of proposed new garden cities, towns and villages.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","60070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673469","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-25","<p>The department did not collect this data over the period in which the coalition government was in power and so we are unfortunately not able to provide this information.</p><p>In Autumn 2015, Government issued guidance to central government departments on how to take social and economic factors into account in their procurements to help level the playing field for UK steel producers. This guidance has now been extended to the wider public sector.</p><p>Since publication of the guidance, Government has been working closely with departments to monitor its impact and ensure delivery. There are no plans to share Government level data publicly, due to its provisional nature.</p><p>On 13th December 2016, the Government published its indicative future steel requirements to 2020, to enable UK steel manufacturers to better plan in advance of future government contracts.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-01-25T17:22:44.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673469/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673469/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Department for Communities and Local Government: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, (a) how much steel in weight his Department has procured, (b) for what purpose that steel was procured and (c) what the countries of origin of that steel were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","60072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673470","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>The call for evidence for the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility closed on 4 December 2016. I and my officials have regular meetings with the Gambling Commission on this and other matters relating to gambling. The Call for Evidence on the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility received 275 responses with a) 29 from local authorities; b) 45 from the gambling industry; c) 29 from interest groups including charities; and d) 167 from the public. The remaining five responses came from MPs.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","60088","2017-01-19T17:09:30.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673470/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673470/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the Gambling Commission after the date of the closure of the call for evidence for the Review of Gaming and Social Responsibility Measures.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","60087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673471","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Information Commissioner's Office’s CCTV code of practice provides guidance and advice to CCTV users on how to comply with the Data Protection Act 1998. The guidance can be found at https://ico.org.uk/media/for-organisations/documents/1542/cctv-code-of-practice.pdf</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-19T12:42:21.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673471/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673471/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","CCTV: Private Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department has issued guidance on privately owned and operated CCTV cameras overlooking neighbouring property.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","60069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673472","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-19","<p>Ministerial colleagues and officials meet regularly to talk about planning policies and legislation. As Lewisham Council are currently considering making a compulsory purchase order to secure land for a proposed regeneration scheme, and any compulsory purchase order has to be submitted to the Secretary of State for confirmation, I cannot comment further at this stage so as not to prejudice his consideration.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-19T16:29:58.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673472/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673472/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-16","Millwall Football Club: Lewisham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with ministerial colleagues and officials on planning policies and legislation that could affect Millwall FC's ability to remain located in Lewisham.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","60083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673473","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>The call for evidence for the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility closed on 4 December 2016. I and my officials have regular meetings with the Gambling Commission on this and other matters relating to gambling. The Call for Evidence on the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility received 275 responses with a) 29 from local authorities; b) 45 from the gambling industry; c) 29 from interest groups including charities; and d) 167 from the public. The remaining five responses came from MPs.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","60087","2017-01-19T17:09:30.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673473/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673473/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many responses her Department has received to the Review of Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures from (a) local authorities, (b) representatives of the gambling industry, (c) charities and (d) individuals.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","60088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673474","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that as we build a country that works for everyone there is opportunity for all to experience and participate in all forms of arts and culture whatever their background.</p><p> </p><p>This is why the Culture White Paper set out a range of commitments aimed at increasing diversity in arts participation. For example, the Cultural Citizens Programme which will provide young people from disadvantaged backgrounds meaningful opportunities to experience the arts. Pilots are taking place in Liverpool and Blackpool, Birmingham, and Barking and Dagenham offering a range of cultural activities so you people develop a lifelong love of the arts.</p><p> </p><p>We have protected funding for Arts Council England (ACE) throughout the next spending period. This includes support for arts programmes which aim to increase access for under-represented groups such as the Creative People and Places programme, in which Arts Council England has invested over £41m to support access to the arts in areas with low engagement in arts and culture.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-19T16:12:02.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673474/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673474/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","Arts: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to encourage young people from disadvantaged backgrounds to participate in (a) drama, (b) music and (c) art.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","60078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673475","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that as we build a country that works for everyone there is opportunity for all to experience and participate in all forms of arts and culture whatever their background.</p><p> </p><p>This is why the Culture White Paper set out a range of commitments aimed at increasing diversity in arts participation. For example, the Cultural Citizens Programme which will provide young people from disadvantaged backgrounds meaningful opportunities to experience the arts. Pilots are taking place in Liverpool and Blackpool, Birmingham, and Barking and Dagenham offering a range of cultural activities so you people develop a lifelong love of the arts.</p><p> </p><p>We have protected funding for Arts Council England (ACE) throughout the next spending period. This includes support for arts programmes which aim to increase access for under-represented groups such as the Creative People and Places programme, in which Arts Council England has invested over £41m to support access to the arts in areas with low engagement in arts and culture.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-19T16:13:24.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673475/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673475/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","Arts: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to encourage young people from disadvantaged backgrounds to participate in (a) drama, (b) music and (c) art.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","60064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673476","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport monitors closely developments relating to proposed changes to library services throughout England. Local authorities have a duty to provide a comprehensive and efficient service that meets local needs within available resources.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2017-01-19T13:59:02.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673476/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673476/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the potential effect on local library provision of changes in government funding for local authorities.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","60025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673477","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>Improving mobile connectivity across the whole of the UK is a priority for the Government. The Ofcom licence obligations arising from the December 2014 agreement mean that the four Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) have a legally binding obligation to provide voice/SMS text coverage to at least 90% of the UK’s landmass by end-2017. Additionally Telefonica (O2) has a licence obligation to deliver indoor 4G coverage to 98% of UK premises (95% in Scotland and the other Devolved Administrations.) The Digital Economy Bill, currently going through Parliament, will give the regulator Ofcom the power to issue large fines to mobile phone companies who fail to meet their licence obligations.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's agreement with the MNOs locked in investment of £5 billion and is delivering improved coverage across the UK. Ofcom's 2016 Connected Nations Report shows that 98% of Scottish premises now have indoor voice coverage and 62% have indoor 4G data coverage from all four MNOs (up from 22% in 2015). Our proposed reforms of the Electronic Communications Code, will support further investment and improvements in connectivity across the UK and reduce not spots.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-19T12:36:27.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673477/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673477/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","Mobile Phones: Lanarkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to improve mobile telephone coverage in Lanarkshire.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","60024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673478","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>Through Sport England, the Government invested over £31.6 million in 2015/16 to supporting football at the grassroots level in England. This included investment made to the Football Association to projects that boost or sustain participation in the sport, and to the Football Foundation to deliver new and improved community sports facilities in towns and cities across the country.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-01-19T17:08:01.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673478/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673478/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","Football: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much the Government invested in grass roots football in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","60181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673479","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>As my Right Hon. Friend, the Secretary of State said in the written statement of 10 January [Vol 619 Col 8WS] , officials have started preliminary work to analyse the relevance of the public interest considerations as set out in the Enterprise Act 2002 to the merger. In doing so, they will look at the available evidence and will consider representations which are relevant to those specified public interests.</p><p> </p><p>While those making representations are free to publish their own views, it would be inappropriate for me to publish representations received as a matter of course in order to ensure those wishing to make representations can do so freely and without risking disclosure of commercially sensitive information. In addition there are specific statutory provisions for the handling of this information and protecting its confidentiality.</p><p> </p><p>We do, however, recognise the importance of transparency in this process and will consider the appropriateness of disclosure of representations made within this context.</p><p> </p><p>We will not be conducting a formal public consultation but will give due regard to any relevant representations in reaching any decision on whether or not to intervene.</p><p> </p><p>As said in the statement of 10 January, we will keep Parliament informed of the process as it moves ahead and will make a further statement when the parties have formally notified the Commission, ahead of making any decision about whether to intervene.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","60152","2017-01-19T16:18:21.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673479/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673479/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","21st Century Fox: Sky","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 16 January 2017 to Question 59468, if she will issue a formal consultation document to invite public representations on public interest considerations relating to the proposed merger of 21st Century Fox and Sky.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","60146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673480","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-19","<p>As my Right Hon. Friend, the Secretary of State said in the written statement of 10 January [Vol 619 Col 8WS] , officials have started preliminary work to analyse the relevance of the public interest considerations as set out in the Enterprise Act 2002 to the merger. In doing so, they will look at the available evidence and will consider representations which are relevant to those specified public interests.</p><p> </p><p>While those making representations are free to publish their own views, it would be inappropriate for me to publish representations received as a matter of course in order to ensure those wishing to make representations can do so freely and without risking disclosure of commercially sensitive information. In addition there are specific statutory provisions for the handling of this information and protecting its confidentiality.</p><p> </p><p>We do, however, recognise the importance of transparency in this process and will consider the appropriateness of disclosure of representations made within this context.</p><p> </p><p>We will not be conducting a formal public consultation but will give due regard to any relevant representations in reaching any decision on whether or not to intervene.</p><p> </p><p>As said in the statement of 10 January, we will keep Parliament informed of the process as it moves ahead and will make a further statement when the parties have formally notified the Commission, ahead of making any decision about whether to intervene.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","60146","2017-01-19T16:18:21.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673480/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673480/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-16","21st Century Fox: Sky","1","House of Commons","T