"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673485","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-19","<p>The information requested can be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-19T16:12:24.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673485/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673485/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Air Force: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many Royal Air Force (a) engineering officers and (b) aircraft technicians have been charged for safety lapses in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","60037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673486","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-19","<p>The following units will form the Strike Experimentation Group (SEG) in 2017:</p><p> </p><p>Household Cavalry Regiment.</p><p> </p><p>Kings Royal Hussars.</p><p> </p><p>1st Battalion Scots Guards.The Highlanders, 4th Battalion Royal Regiment of Scotland.</p><p> </p><p>1st Regiment Royal Logistics Corps.</p><p> </p><p>1st (Close Support) Battalion Royal Electrical Mechanical Engineers.</p><p> </p><p>The SEG will work with other units, including those in the Royal Artillery, from across the Army. 3rd Regiment Royal Horse Artillery will be assigned to the SEG from 2020, when the SEG will form the first Strike brigade.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","60035","2017-01-19T16:11:50.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673486/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673486/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Army: Warminster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which of the Army's current units will form the planned strike experimental group based in Warminster.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","60034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673487","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-19","<p>The following units will form the Strike Experimentation Group (SEG) in 2017:</p><p> </p><p>Household Cavalry Regiment.</p><p> </p><p>Kings Royal Hussars.</p><p> </p><p>1st Battalion Scots Guards.The Highlanders, 4th Battalion Royal Regiment of Scotland.</p><p> </p><p>1st Regiment Royal Logistics Corps.</p><p> </p><p>1st (Close Support) Battalion Royal Electrical Mechanical Engineers.</p><p> </p><p>The SEG will work with other units, including those in the Royal Artillery, from across the Army. 3rd Regiment Royal Horse Artillery will be assigned to the SEG from 2020, when the SEG will form the first Strike brigade.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","60034","2017-01-19T16:11:51.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673487/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673487/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Artillery: Warminster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what artillery will be assigned to the planned strike experimental group based in Warminster.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","60035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673488","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-19","<p>The information requested is provided below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Equipment</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>51mm Mortar</p></td><td><p>Nil – no longer in service</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>81mm Mortar (L16A1)</p></td><td><p>143</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>81mm Mortar (L16A3)</p></td><td><p>314</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>105mm Light Gun</p></td><td><p>126</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>AS90</p></td><td><p>89</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Guided Multiple Launch Rocket System (GMLRS)</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>We do not routinely comment on the specific status of equipment as to do so would compromise operational security and would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-19T16:13:54.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673488/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673488/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Armed Forces: Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) 51mm light mortars, (b) 81mm mortars, (c) 105mm light guns, (d) AS90 artillery guns and (e) 227mm multiple-launch rocket systems are (i) in service and (ii) fit for purpose.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","60036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673489","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-23","<p>HMS Queen Elizabeth is expected to undergo sea trials this summer.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-23T17:21:08.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673489/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673489/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when in 2017 he expects HMS Queen Elizabeth to begin platform sea trials.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","60000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673490","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Royal Navy and the Ministry of Defence continuously review the capabilities required to deliver Royal Navy tasking, including how the Royal Navy might broaden the existing air defence and combat management systems.</p><p>I am withholding further detail as its disclosure would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-24T15:04:19.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673490/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673490/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has for acquiring an integrated air and missile defence capability for the Royal Navy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","60001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673491","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-23","<p>We continually assess the capability of the United Kingdom's nuclear submarine fleet to ensure its operational effectiveness and to maintain resilience against potential threats.</p><p>I am withholding information on the specific systems used by our submarines as disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of our Armed Forces.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-23T17:50:29.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673491/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673491/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Nuclear Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that Britain's nuclear submarine fleet systems have robust and up-to-date operating systems installed in place of Windows XP.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","60008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673492","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-19","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given by my noble Friend, the Minister of State in the House of Lords, Earl Howe, to the noble Lord, Lord Campbell of Pittenweem, in the House of Lords to Question HL2386.</p><p>The Medium Wheeled Gun System project is still undergoing pre-concept phase work. A decision on the concept and assessment phases of the project is not expected to be made before April 2017.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-19T16:08:21.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673492/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673492/answer","Hansard Extract  26 October 2016, HL 2386.docx","Hansard Extract  26 October 2016, HL 2386.docx","Artillery:Procurement","Artillery:Procurement","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673492/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Artillery: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress has been made on the Medium Wheeled Gun System project.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","60107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673493","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-23","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not hold a complete central record of the volume and origin of steel used in defence projects by our prime contractors over the last five years.</p><p>The largest project, the aircraft carriers, has used 95,000 tonnes of steel, 88%of which was British. The Government has published its future pipeline for steel requirements in December 2016, which indicates the quantities of steel expected to be required for major projects, including defence. This will enable UK steel manufacturers to better plan and bid for Government contracts. The pipeline is published on gov.uk at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-policy-note-1116-procuring-steel-in-major-projects-revised-guidance.</p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) has also published updated policy guidance on steel procurement in major Government projects. This aims to ensure that the public sector, including defence, takes full account of the value provided by UK steel producers when conducting procurement activities. BEIS is working closely with Departments to monitor its impact and ensure compliance.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-01-23T17:43:44.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673493/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673493/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-16","Ministry of Defence: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, (a) how much steel in weight his Department has procured, (b) for what purpose that steel was procured and (c) what the countries of origin of that steel were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","60073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673494","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>Information specifically relating to UK nationals enrolled at higher education institutions (HEIs) in other EU countries is not available.</p><p>Eurostat collects data primarily on the basis of the country in which students completed their secondary schooling. In absence of this, they collect data on the basis of the students’ usual or permanent residence prior to their higher education studies, or their citizenship. Eurostat data shows that approximately 13,000 students whose country of origin was the UK were enrolled in HEIs in EU countries in academic year 2013/14, and approximately 5,000 were studying first degrees.</p><p>Eurostat publishes these statistics on their website and they can be accessed using the web tool at the following link: <a href="http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=educ_uoe_mobs02&amp;lang=en" target="_blank">http://appsso.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/nui/show.do?dataset=educ_uoe_mobs02&amp;lang=en</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-19T17:28:22.63Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673494/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673494/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Foreign Students: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many UK nationals are currently enrolled on an undergraduate degree at a university in another EU country.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","60112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673496","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. The Department for Education’s annual School Workforce Census does not include the nationality of teachers or the location of where they qualified to become a teacher.</p><p>The Department does publish statistics showing awards of qualified teacher status to teachers from the European Economic Area. See Table 8 of the ‘Initial teacher training: trainee number census - 2016 to 2017’ statistical release published on</p><p>November 24 2016: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2016-to-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","60063","2017-01-19T09:36:09.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673496/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673496/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Teachers: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of (a) registered and (b) practising school teachers obtained their initial teaching qualification in an EU country other than the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","60100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673497","Department for Education","false","2017-01-24","<p>The figures are publicly available from the annual School Workforce Census’ statistical first releases, at the following web link: <br>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-workforce</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","60116","2017-01-24T10:01:38.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673497/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673497/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Music: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many music teachers there were in schools in England in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","60115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673498","Department for Education","false","2017-01-24","<p>The figures are publicly available from the annual School Workforce Census’ statistical first releases, at the following web link: <br>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-workforce</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","60115","2017-01-24T10:01:38.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673498/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673498/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Arts: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many art teachers there were in schools in England in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","60116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673499","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. The Department for Education’s annual School Workforce Census does not include the nationality of teachers or the location of where they qualified to become a teacher.</p><p>The Department does publish statistics showing awards of qualified teacher status to teachers from the European Economic Area. See Table 8 of the ‘Initial teacher training: trainee number census - 2016 to 2017’ statistical release published on</p><p>November 24 2016: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2016-to-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","60100","2017-01-19T09:36:09.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673499/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673499/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Teachers: Qualifications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of (a) registered and (b) active school teachers obtained their initial teaching qualification in an EU country other than the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","60063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673500","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department is aware of the excellent work schools and teachers are doing to offer students extra-curricular activities and experiences outside the classroom. These activities make a significant contribution to young people’s non-cognitive skills and development, as well as their attainment.</p><p>Since the March 2016 budget, the Department has been reviewing how funding from the soft drinks industry levy could be used to help schools offer a wider range of activities and support pupils’ health. The department is currently determining the details how this funding will be allocated and we will provide further details in due course.</p><p>Therefore the Department does not currently invite applications from secondary schools, nor has the Department granted funding to schools specifically for the purpose of extending their school day at this time. As a result we are unable to provide the information requested.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","60086","2017-01-19T09:41:10.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673500/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673500/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","School Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications her Department has received from secondary schools wishing to extend their school day.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","60085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673501","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department is aware of the excellent work schools and teachers are doing to offer students extra-curricular activities and experiences outside the classroom. These activities make a significant contribution to young people’s non-cognitive skills and development, as well as their attainment.</p><p>Since the March 2016 budget, the Department has been reviewing how funding from the soft drinks industry levy could be used to help schools offer a wider range of activities and support pupils’ health. The department is currently determining the details how this funding will be allocated and we will provide further details in due course.</p><p>Therefore the Department does not currently invite applications from secondary schools, nor has the Department granted funding to schools specifically for the purpose of extending their school day at this time. As a result we are unable to provide the information requested.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","60085","2017-01-19T09:41:10.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673501/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673501/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Secondary Education: Extended Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many secondary schools have been granted funding to extend their current school day.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","60086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673502","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>The free schools programme is a demand-led programme. We assess applications to establish free schools against published criteria. At the beginning of each application wave we write to local authorities to ask for their views about any free school applications received. We consult them again about the ones that have been invited to attend an interview and then again about the ones that are proceeding to the next stage of the process, the pre-opening stage. In addition Lord Nash writes to all the relevant Hon. Members at the end of the application wave to let them know which applications in their constituencies have been successful.</p><p>Under section 10 of the Academies Act 2010 the trust behind the proposal must consult the people they think appropriate on whether to enter into a funding agreement with the Secretary of State. The funding agreement needs to be signed before the school can open. This statutory consultation informs stakeholders and the local community about the project and gives them the opportunity to comment on it.</p><p>We are continually looking for ways to improve the application process.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-23T13:40:47.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673502/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673502/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will review the free school application process to ensure that hon. Members, local councillors and other relevant stakeholders are kept informed of proposed developments in their area.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","60009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673503","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>The department has published information on the numbers of exclusions by detailed school type including maintained schools, academies, and free schools for 2012/13 to 2014/15, but not for community schools and foundation schools. These can be found in the underlying data of ‘Permanent and fixed-period exclusions in England: 2014 to 2015’<sup>1</sup> and are reproduced in the accompanying table.</p><p> </p><p>Exclusions figures for grammar schools are not published and are also included in the attached table.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-23T11:21:37.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673503/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673503/answer","60040 table attachment.xlsx","60040 table attachment.xlsx","Exclusions figures for grammar schools","Exclusions figures for grammar schools","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673503/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to provide information on how many pupils were excluded from (a) community schools, (b) foundation schools, (c) free schools, (d) academies and (e) grammar schools in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","60040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673504","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>The Department held a Holocaust Memorial event on Monday 16 January. All of the staff were invited to a talk given by Harry Spiro, a Holocaust survivor.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-23T16:19:32.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673504/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673504/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Holocaust Memorial Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans her Department has to mark Holocaust Memorial Day.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","59999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673505","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>We want schools to be supported to encourage pupils to lead healthier lifestyles.</p><p>The Healthy Schools Rating Scheme will provide schools with the tools to assess how well they encourage their children to eat a nutritious diet and lead an active lifestyle, and how they can improve. Healthy eating will be a core strand of the scheme but the detailed criteria have not yet been developed. Over the next month, we will be exploring the design and delivery options further with potential suppliers through pre-market engagement discussions. Further details will be announced in due course.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-23T11:17:50.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673505/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673505/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Healthy Schools Rating Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the proposed healthy rating scheme, outlined in Childhood obesity: a plan for action, published in August 2016, will include a criterion on compliance with school food standards for food served across the whole day.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","60005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673506","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>We are considering the responses to the consultation on the implementation of the EBacc. We will publish the results of the consultation, including the number of responses and the Government response in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","60007","2017-01-23T11:37:05.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673506/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673506/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to publish the findings and conclusions of its consultation on implementing the English baccalaureate.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","60006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673507","Department for Education","false","2017-01-23","<p>We are considering the responses to the consultation on the implementation of the EBacc. We will publish the results of the consultation, including the number of responses and the Government response in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","60006","2017-01-23T11:37:05.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673507/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673507/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many submissions were made to her Department's consultation on implementing the English baccalaureate.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","60007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673508","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Department has spent no money to date on advertising on the change to numerical grading for GCSE exams. Instead, we have been working closely with Ofqual, awarding organisations and key bodies such as the Confederation for British Industry (CBI) and Universities and College Admission Service (UCAS) to communicate the changes to GCSEs to key audiences, particularly schools, colleges and universities. In 2016 we produced a joint slide pack with Ofqual that was sent to all schools in England, which can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/qualifications-reform-resources-for-teachers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/qualifications-reform-resources-for-teachers</a></p><p>Over the coming months we expect to fund targeted communications, particularly directed to parents and employers as we move towards the award of the first new GCSEs in August 2017.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-19T17:57:14.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673508/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673508/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on advertising the change to numerical grading for GCSE exams.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","60029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673509","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Government is currently considering the evidence received from the Call for Evidence on accelerated courses and switching university or degree. A summary of findings was published on 20 December 2016 and is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579438/Findings_from_the_Call_for_Evidence_on_Accelerated_Courses_and_Switching_University_or_Degree.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579438/Findings_from_the_Call_for_Evidence_on_Accelerated_Courses_and_Switching_University_or_Degree.pdf</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-19T17:37:54.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673509/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673509/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Higher Education: Part-time Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 23 November 2016 to Question 53834, when she plans to publish the Government's response to its call for evidence on credit transfers for part-time learners.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","60186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673510","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Government believes part-time education and adult education bring enormous benefits to individuals, the economy and employers. In our recent guidance to the Director of Fair Access, we asked the Director to provide a renewed focus on part-time study because of the contribution this makes to widening participation, recognising that the traditional three-year degree does not suit some learners and may discourage their participation.</p><p>The new Office for Students (OfS), as proposed in the Higher Education and Research Bill, will promote student choice, and by allowing new providers into the system, prospective students can expect greater part-time and distance learning opportunities, including for mature learners. For example, we know that in 2014/15, 56 per cent of students attending new providers designated for Student Loans Company support were over the age of 25, compared to 23 per cent at traditional higher education providers.</p><p>The Higher Education and Research Bill also places a general duty on the OfS to have regard to the need to promote choice and opportunity for students. This duty is broad and intended to ensure that the OfS looks across the whole range of different modes of study and student needs, including part-time study and life-long learning.</p><p>The reforms proposed by the Higher Education and Research Bill complement the practical support government is already giving to part-time students, which includes providing tuition fee loans and relaxing the rules on funding second degrees. We are also consulting on providing, for the first time ever, part-time maintenance loans.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-19T17:38:08.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673510/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673510/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Office for Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to ensure that the proposed Office for Students prioritises the promotion  of part-time and lifelong learning.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","60187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673511","Department for Education","false","2017-01-19","<p>The department has commissioned a small scale, qualitative research study to understand the scope and profile of out-of-normal timetable activities offered by a sample of secondary schools in England and the challenges related to offering these activities.</p><p>The research is investigating barriers and enablers for schools in regards to offering these activities, parent and pupil perceptions and the role that external providers, for example voluntary sector and commercial providers play, in supporting schools with their offer.</p><p>The department has previously commissioned evaluations of programmes involving extension of the school day or provision of extra-curricular activities and services, including Full Service Extended Schools and Extended Services schools.</p><p> </p><p>Evaluation of Extended Services (2012)</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/extended-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/extended-schools</a></p><p> </p><p>Evaluation of Full Service Extended Schools (2007/8)</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130401151715/http:/www.education.gov.uk/publications/eOrderingDownload/RR852.pdf" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130401151715/http:/www.education.gov.uk/publications/eOrderingDownload/RR852.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Impact of Study Support (2001)</p><p><a href="https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/4154458.pdf" target="_blank">https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/4154458.pdf</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-19T09:39:54.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673511/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673511/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","Secondary Education: Extended Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what research her Department has commissioned on the potential benefits and costs of extending the school day in secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","60179"
