"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673521","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Food Standards Agency in Northern Ireland has not routinely gathered information on prosecutions and has not otherwise been made aware of any such prosecutions in Northern Ireland since 2007.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-19T17:19:25.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673521/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673521/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Infant Foods: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many retailers in Northern Ireland have been fined for failure to comply with the Infant Formula and Follow-on Formula (Northern Ireland) Regulations 2007 in each year since 2007.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","60133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673522","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Food Standards Agency in Wales does not routinely collate specific information on businesses that have been prosecuted, and has not otherwise been made aware of any such prosecutions in Wales since 2007.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-19T17:16:46.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673522/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673522/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Infant Foods: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many retailers in Wales have been fined for not complying with the Infant Formula and Follow-on Formula (Wales) Regulations 2007 in each year since 2007.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","60180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673523","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Food Standards Agency has recently established a central register of successful food law prosecutions and has not been made aware of any such prosecutions in England.</p><p> </p><p>Monitoring food businesses to ensure compliance with food legislation is the responsibility of local authorities. Local authorities are also responsible for taking enforcement action, including prosecutions, where non-compliance is found.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-19T17:18:10.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673523/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673523/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Infant Foods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many retailers in England have been fined for failure to comply with the Infant Formula and Follow-on Formula (England) Regulations 2007 in each year since 2007.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","60132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673524","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-24","<p>The department was not collecting this data over the period in question so we are unfortunately not able to provide this information.</p><p> </p><p>In Autumn 2015, Government issued guidance to central government departments on how to take social and economic factors into account in their procurements to help level the playing field for UK steel producers. This guidance has now been extended to the wider public sector.</p><p> </p><p>Since publication of the guidance, Government has been working closely with departments to monitor its impact and ensure delivery. There are no plans to share Government level data publicly, due to its provisional nature.</p><p> </p><p>On 13th December 2016, the Government published its indicative future steel requirements to 2020, to enable UK steel manufacturers to better plan in advance of future government contracts.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-24T17:52:23.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673524/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673524/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-16","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, (a) how much steel in weight her Department has procured, (b) for what purpose that steel was procured and (c) what the countries of origin of that steel were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","60074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673525","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>This is a British Council project which is funded through surplus generated by the commercial activity of the British Council. No additional Exchequer funding was made available for this project. China has begun a huge investment in football and this project is helping to establish the UK as their priority partner for sport. It will help to promote UK football in a major market, leading to long-term cultural and economic gains for the UK.</p><p>The British Council has advised that the programme is generating direct economic benefits for UK Higher Education and training sectors, and has helped to create the condition for indirect benefits across the wider sporting sector in relation to the establishment of private training academies, sports infrastructure, sports technology, sports TV and merchandising rights.</p><p>A letter from the Chief Executive of the British Council providing an update on the project to date will be placed in the Library of the House within ten working days.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-19T17:30:30.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673525/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673525/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","China: Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 59261, on football: China, if he will publish the advice he received before the decision was made to allocate that funding.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","60129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673526","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The British Council has confirmed that there will be annual progress reports and a full evaluation will be undertaken on completion of the programme in 2020.</p><p>The programme started in 2016-17. The British Council anticipates the first report being completed in May 2017, assessing the first year of the programme.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-19T17:33:00.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673526/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673526/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","China: Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 59261, on football: China, when he plans to assess the effect of the funding provided.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","60130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673527","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>From within Europe, we transferred over 900 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children to the UK in 2016 under the Dublin Regulation and section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. In 2015, there were around 20 transfers of unaccompanied asylum-seeking children to the UK from Europe under the Dublin Regulation.</p><p>From outside of Europe, 2,059 children were resettled to the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme in year ending September 2016.</p><p>The UK also supports refugee children to enter the UK via our Gateway and Mandate resettlement schemes and our refugee family reunion policy, however the published statistics do not break down these figures by those aged over and under 18.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-19T13:43:40.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673527/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673527/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-16","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refugee children have been supported to enter the UK in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","60114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673528","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The British Council is directly managing the UK's contribution to this programme. It is not allocating funding to other organisations. In addition to the UK's £3 million allocation, the Chinese partners have invested a significantly higher sum which will be directly invested in the UK, for example through payment to UK Universities and UK training organisations for 600 Chinese coaches to train in the UK.</p><p>China has begun a huge investment in football and this project is helping to establish the UK as their priority partner for sport. It will help to promote UK football in a major market, leading to long-term cultural and economic gains for the UK, which may include benefits across the wider sporting sector in relation to the establishment of private training academies, sports infrastructure, sports technology, sports TV and merchandising rights.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-19T17:36:01.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673528/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673528/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","China: Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 59261, on football: China, which organisations the funding was allocated to.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","60131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673529","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Coalition announced the formation of the Joint Incident Assessment Team (JIAT) in May 2016 and gave further details of the composition and investigation process during a press conference on 4 August. They conveyed that the JIAT would comprise representation from 6 Coalition countries, would operate with independence and neutrality, and will conduct investigations in accordance with international processes.</p><p>The UK has not been directly involved in investigations undertaken by the JIAT, but has supported its development, including through the delivery of training sessions and meetings.</p><p>Appointments made to the JIAT are a matter for the Coalition to respond to.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-24T16:09:27.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673529/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673529/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the capacity of the Joint Incident Assessment Team to conduct effective investigations into breaches of international humanitarian law in Yemen; and what representations he (a) made and (b) received on the appointment of Mansoor Al-Mansoor to that team.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","60043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673530","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>A number of our High Commissions and Embassies now do so, but we do not centrally hold details of the wine that is served.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-24T16:02:46.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673530/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673530/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","Embassies: Wines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what proportion of UK High Commissions and embassies serve English or Welsh wine.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","59993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673531","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>We continue to lobby all parties to the conflict to facilitate commercial and humanitarian access. The UK Government is providing £1.4 million for the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism to speed up the clearance process for ships, which should in turn help with the continued delivery of food to Yemen by sea.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-24T16:06:48.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673531/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673531/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","Yemen: Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken to ensure continuity of food deliveries by sea to all ports in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","60002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673532","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Government is aware of the issue regarding Yemeni importers’ access to finance for food imports and continues to lobby all parties to the conflict to facilitate commercial access.</p><p>The Department for International Development (DfID) is providing £1.4 million for the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism (UNVIM) to speed up the clearance process for ships, improve commercial confidence and reduce the price of basic goods. DfID officials are engaging with a range of partners to understand the issues for importer access to finance and explore potential solutions.</p><p>UK Export Finance has not been approached to provide credit guarantees for exports to Yemen, and is currently off cover due to the extremely poor risk outlook.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-24T17:58:34.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673532/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673532/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-16","Yemen: Food Supply","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if the Government will offer credit guarantees to commercial shipping agents to ensure future food supplies to Yemen.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","60003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673533","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-23","<p>The UK is not providing direct technical assistance to the Central Bank of Yemen (CBY) in Aden. However, we are working closely with other donors to look at ways to support the CBY to continue to function, pay salaries across the country, and pay for essential food and fuel imports.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-01-23T16:53:44.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673533/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673533/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-16","Central Bank of Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what technical assistance the Government has given the government of Yemen to help ensure that the Central Bank of Yemen remains fully operational while its headquarters is moved to Aden.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","60004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673534","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>When the Foreign Secretary summoned the Russian and Iranian ambassadors on 15 December, he made clear that; &quot;both Russia and Iran have failed to uphold their obligations under international humanitarian law, specifically by failing to facilitate the delivery of humanitarian aid to civilians during the months when eastern Aleppo was besieged.&quot; The Iranian Foreign Ministry responded that the statements issued by the Foreign Secretary were &quot;unrealistic, unconsidered and destructive&quot;. On 19 December, Russia joined the UN Security Council members in voting in favour of UN Security Council Resolution 2328 on the humanitarian situation in Aleppo. The resolution requested the UN to monitor evacuations from Eastern Aleppo and demanded all parties provide the UN with safe, immediate and unimpeded access. The UK continues to urge Russia and Iran to use their influence to implement fully the terms of this UNSCR as well as the ceasefire deal they announced on 30 December</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-24T15:55:05.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673534/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673534/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 22 December 2016 to Question 57916, on Syria: armed conflict, what response his Department has received from Russian and Iranian ambassadors following the meeting on 15 December 2016.","false","Biography information for Alex Salmond","Gordon","Alex Salmond","59995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673535","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>​I refer the Hon. Member to the answer that I gave on 12 January 2017 to Written Question 58382.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-24T15:57:57.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673535/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673535/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-16","Serbia: Official Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what preparations (a) his Department and (b) the British Embassy in Belgrade undertook in advance of his official visit to Serbia in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","60166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673536","Home Office","false","2017-01-19","<p>The UK has contributed significantly to hosting, supporting and protecting the most vulnerable children affected by the migration crisis. In the year ending September 2016, we granted asylum or another form of leave to over 8,000 children in the UK. The Government has also established a £10 million Refugee Children Fund to support the needs of vulnerable refugee and migrant children arriving in Europe.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, we transferred over 900 unaccompanied asylum seeking children from within Europe to the UK. More eligible children will be transferred from Europe under the Immigration Act 2016 in the coming months and we will continue to meet our obligations under the Dublin Regulation to reunite asylum seeking children with their close families.</p><p> </p><p>Unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children are supported by local authorities in accordance with the relevant children’s legislation in England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. In July last year the Government introduced the National Transfer Scheme to ensure there is a more even distribution of caring responsibilities for unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children across the country. To support the scheme, the Home Office significantly increased the funding available to local authorities for the care and support of unaccompanied children.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-01-19T13:29:53.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673536/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673536/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-16","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the UK is taking to provide support for refugee children in (a) Europe and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","60137"
