"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673540","Department of Health","false","2017-01-20","<p>NHS England intends to publish its impact assessment in due course.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-20T14:20:36.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673540/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673540/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Royal Brompton Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the impact assessment made on (a) NHS England's proposed closure of congenital heart disease services at Royal Brompton Hospital and (b) the potential transfer of patients from that hospital to (i) Great Ormand Street Hospital, (ii) Barts Hospital, (iii) St Thomas' Hospital and (iv) other hospitals.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","60182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673541","Department of Health","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Clinical Evaluation Team attends and updates industry at the NHS Supplier Board meetings. As part of the stakeholder engagement process, the team will decide if an initial introductory meeting is required with suppliers to explain the process for clinical review and how they can contribute by providing product information. This may be followed by specific supplier meetings or call for action letters, if required.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-24T16:27:07.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673541/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673541/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Medical Treatments: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms the NHS Clinical Evaluation Team's process to review NHS products uses to engage with industry.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","60185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673542","Department of Health","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Clinical Evaluation Team considered that in order for the team to be acting reasonably it should give suppliers the opportunity to correct factual inaccuracies and errors about their products before the team published their reports. The Clinical Evaluation Team considered that a minimum period of 72 hours ahead of publication would be a reasonable period for suppliers to alert the team to any such factual and material errors or mistakes that may have been made against those reviews. This minimum period is a starting point for suppliers and the team may give suppliers more time if in the circumstances it is reasonable to do so.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-24T16:29:52.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673542/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673542/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Medical Treatments: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons manufacturers have been given 72 hours to comment on the draft assessment results of their products as part of the NHS Clinical Evaluation Team's process to review NHS products; and whether this is considered best practice.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","60184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673543","Department of Health","false","2017-01-20","<p>As part of its ongoing work to help providers meet the new congenital heart disease commissioning standards NHS England is undertaking assessments to establish the impact its proposals might have on interventional and surgical services, including considering issues such as capacity and workforce.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-20T14:21:50.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673543/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673543/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Royal Brompton Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of additional (a) staff, (b) wards and (c) beds that will be required in each of the hospitals that will take patients transferred from the Royal Brompton Hospital in the event of the closure of that hospital's congenital heart disease services.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","60183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673544","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>Lord Carter’s Report ‘Operational productivity and performance in English NHS acute hospitals’ recognised the need for making improvements in procurement within the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is already working on initiatives that include the new NHS Supply Chain delivery model, the ‘Model Hospital’, Procurement Price Index tools and ‘Scan4Safety’, enabling improved patient safety, clinical productivity and supply chain efficiency.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T16:07:29.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673544/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673544/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","NHS: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent progress he has made on improving procurement in the NHS; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","60171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673545","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The Accident and Emergency (A&amp;E) Improvement Plan was launched by NHS England and NHS Improvement in July 2016. It sets out five key initiatives that systems should be adopting across their local Urgent and Emergency Care pathways to improve national performance against the A&amp;E waiting time standard that 95% of patients wait for less than four hours before they are admitted, discharged or transferred to another hospital, by the end of March 2017. As part of the plan, systems are segmented on the basis of performance with targeted support provided by the Emergency Care Improvement Programme and regional NHS England and NHS Improvement teams to unblock barriers, embed best practice and share lessons learnt with the rest of the National Health Service.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T16:40:55.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673545/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673545/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms are in place to disseminate best practice relating to the provision of accident and emergency care.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","60172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673546","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>3,019 medical students were accepted for general practice training in 2016 – the highest number in any year to date.</p><p> </p><p>The ‘General Practice Forward View’, published by NHS England in April 2016, set out their plans of delivering growth in the general practitioner (GP) workforce. This includes work by Health Education England (HEE) to increase the number of medical school graduates choosing general practice. HEE is working with the Medical Schools Council, higher education institutions, the Royal College of General Practitioners (RCGP) and the British Medical Association’s General Practitioners Committee to increase the profile of general practice in medical schools. A working group, chaired by Professor Valerie Wass OBE, published recommendations on 8 November 2016.</p><p> </p><p>HEE and the RCGP will continue to develop the current recruitment campaign to raise the profile of general practice as a career. The campaign showcases the variety of different opportunities and the flexibility of the specialty, as well as the central role that GPs play in the community and their patients’ care. HEE has recruited and trained 35 campaign ambassadors and advocates to support and promote national and regional activities including attendance at recruitment events and through social media.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-19T11:45:16.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673546/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673546/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Doctors: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to increase the number of medical students going into general practice.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","60173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673547","Department of Health","false","2017-01-24","<p>Suppliers will be provided with copies of the Clinical Evaluation Team’s evaluation reports on their products at least 72 hours before the publication date in order to give them the opportunity to correct factual inaccuracies and errors about their products. After taking into consideration any such factual inaccuracies and errors notified by suppliers, the Clinical Evaluation Team will then publish the final report containing all products assessed on its website.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-24T16:10:12.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673547/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673547/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Medical Treatments: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether manufacturers will see evaluation reports and comparative summaries of products reviewed by the NHS Clinical Evaluation Team before they are made publicly available.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","60200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673548","Department of Health","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Clinical Evaluation Team has published an operating manual, entitled “NHS Clinical Evaluation Team: Operating Manual” which can be found on the Clinical Evaluation Team’s section of NHS Business Services Authority website:</p><p><a href="http://www.nhsbsa.nhs.uk/CET" target="_blank">www.nhsbsa.nhs.uk/CET</a></p><p> </p><p>This manual explains the process of developing the clinical criteria for each product group.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-24T16:28:41.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673548/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673548/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Medical Treatments: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the NHS Business Services Authority is taking to ensure that the criteria for the review of NHS products by the NHS Clinical Evaluation Team are made public to patients and industry.","false","Biography information for Alan Johnson","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Alan Johnson","60201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673549","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The new congenital heart disease (CHD) standards were approved by the NHS England Board in July 2015. The paper which NHS England’s CHD review team submitted to the Board at that time set out that:</p><p> </p><p>“We found no published evidence on the effects of proximity of other services so the proposed standards are based on expert opinion. Our clinical advisers strongly advocated co-location with other paediatric services, though they recognised that not everyone agrees. They considered that while responsiveness was one important factor, it was not the only thing that mattered. Delivering these services effectively requires the input of the wider paediatric multidisciplinary team, and the interaction between these teams on a daily basis, when co-located, is considered to be of significant benefit to patients.”</p><p> </p><p>The full paper can be found on NHS England’s website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Item-4-CHD-Report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Item-4-CHD-Report.pdf</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T16:39:51.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673549/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673549/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Heart Diseases: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish the evidence indicating the clinical benefits of the co-location of children's services with children congenital heart disease services that supported its inclusion in the final standards for congenital heart disease contained in the New Congenital Heart Disease Review: Final Report.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","60193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673550","Department of Health","false","2017-01-24","<p>The National Audit Office published an estimate of the total amount spent on cancer care in the National Health Service to show the relative scale of the cost of cancer services to the NHS. The NHS does not routinely publish estimates of the total amount spent on cancer patients as the large scale and highly complex range of services that cancer patients interact with makes this very difficult. Many of the services used by people with cancer, in particular diagnostic and rehabilitation services, but also some treatment services, are not specific to cancer patients.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-24T11:45:27.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673550/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673550/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Cancer: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the National Audit Office's report, Progress in improving cancer services and outcomes in England, published in January 2015, what the total spend on cancer care in the NHS per newly diagnosed patient was for the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","59996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673551","Department for Education","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Immigration Skills Charge will be paid by UK employers recruiting workers from outside the European Economic Area (EEA) through the Tier 2 skilled worker route. There are no plans to extend the charge to employers recruiting from the European Economic Area post-Brexit.</p><p> </p><p>We have not estimated the potential annual cost to the NHS of the Immigration Skills Charge. The cost to the NHS will depend on its use of the Tier 2 skilled worker route.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","60015","2017-01-25T14:03:12.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673551/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673551/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to extend an Immigration Skills Charge to (a) new and (b) existing NHS clinical staff recruited from the European Economic Area (EEA) in the event of the UK leaving the EEA.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","60013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673552","Department of Health","false","2017-01-19","<p>The latest information available is presented in the following table.</p><p> </p><p>Joiners to the National Health Service by nationality group, which is self reported, in NHS trusts and clinical commissioning groups in England, 30 September 2015 to 30 September 2016.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Headcount</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All nationalities</p></td><td><p>155,997</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>United Kingdom</p></td><td><p>117,795</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>European Economic Area excluding UK</p></td><td><p>15,052</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rest of the world</p></td><td><p>13,149</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Unknown</p></td><td><p>10,024</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source:</em> NHS Digital, NHS Hospital &amp; Community Health Service workforce statistics.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-19T14:30:49.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673552/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673552/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people who joined the NHS workforce in England in the last 12 month period for which figures are available are known to have (a) British nationality, (b) European Economic Area nationality other than British and (c) another nationality.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","60014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673553","Department for Education","false","2017-01-25","<p>The Immigration Skills Charge will be paid by UK employers recruiting workers from outside the European Economic Area (EEA) through the Tier 2 skilled worker route. There are no plans to extend the charge to employers recruiting from the European Economic Area post-Brexit.</p><p> </p><p>We have not estimated the potential annual cost to the NHS of the Immigration Skills Charge. The cost to the NHS will depend on its use of the Tier 2 skilled worker route.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","60013","2017-01-25T14:03:12.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673553/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673553/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-16","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the potential annual cost to the NHS of the introduction of the Immigration Skills Charge (a) from April 2017 and (b) in the event of that charge being extended to cover nationals of countries within the European Economic Area after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","60015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673554","Department of Health","false","2017-01-20","<p>The opportunities and limitations of the linear programming model, as well as other proposed approaches for revising the Eatwell Guide, are detailed in the Public Health England report ‘From Plate to Guide: What, why and how for the eatwell model’, which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579388/eatwell_model_guide_report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/579388/eatwell_model_guide_report.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The model was informed by an External Reference Group operating transparently. The visual approach was further tested through public research.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-20T11:43:27.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673554/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673554/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Nutrition: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 58477, on nutrition: health education, what advantages and disadvantages were considered and identified by Public Health England when the external reference group recommended using the linear programming model to revise the Eatwell Guide.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","59994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673555","Department of Health","false","2017-01-24","<p>The Government’s mandate to NHS England for 2016-17 set a clear expectation that carers should routinely be identified by services and given access to information and advice about the support available.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s mandate to NHS England for 2017-18 is currently being developed in consultation with NHS England and Healthwatch England, and will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>Discussions are ongoing between the Government and NHS England to develop a range of actions to further support carers through the forthcoming Carers Strategy.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-24T11:36:04.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673555/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/673555/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-16","Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions the Government has had with NHS England on ensuring that the mandate to NHS England for 2017-18 reflects the Government's plans to improve support for carers through its forthcoming Carers Strategy.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","59992"
